Issues.Body:
> **TL;DR — it breaks an exclusive accordion.** In an accordion (or tab group / expandable nav menu) where opening one panel closes the currently-open one, clicking a different panel makes the open panel **disappear instantly instead of animating its `animate.leave` collapse**. The opening panel's `animate.enter` plays fine; only the *closing* panel is broken, and only when another opens in the same change-detection tick.
>
> It's **order-dependent**: it only breaks when the closing section comes *before* the opening one in DOM order. (Both sections update in one tick, in order — so the closing element is detached and tracked *first*, then the entering sibling cancels it.) Closing a *later* section while opening an *earlier* one animates fine, as does toggling a single section with nothing else opening. So in the repro, **clicking Section B while A is open is broken; clicking Section A while B is open animates correctly** — don't be fooled by trying the working direction.
>
> Why: the panels are separate instances of the **same** item component, so their animated elements share one `TNode`. `cancelLeavingNodes` (added in 21.2.0) sees the still-animating closing panel under that shared `TNode` in a different DOM parent, assumes it's a stale duplicate, and force-removes it.
>
> ▶️ **Repro — same code, side by side** (a two-section exclusive accordion; click **Section B** while **Section A** is open):
> - ❌ **Broken (Angular 21.2.x):** https://stackblitz.com/github/kaiguogit/ng-animate-leave-repro — Panel A vanishes instantly.
> - ✅ **Works (Angular 21.1.6):** https://stackblitz.com/github/kaiguogit/ng-animate-leave-repro/tree/angular-21.1 — Panel A shrinks smoothly over 600 ms.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

Yes — works in 21.1.x, broken since 21.2.0.

### Description

When two **separate instances of the same component/template** are toggled in the same change-detection tick — one element leaving via `animate.leave` while a sibling instance's element enters via `animate.enter` — the leaving element is **removed from the DOM synchronously and its leave animation never runs**.

This is the generalized form of the drag-and-drop regression #67257. PR #67361 fixed the case where the leaving element *is* the re-inserted element (a node move), but the underlying cause — `cancelLeavingNodes` force-removing any tracked leaving node whose parent differs from the entering node's parent — is unchanged and still bites whenever the leaving/entering elements are **distinct nodes that share a `TNode`**.

This is extremely common: accordions, tab groups, exclusive-expansion menus, master/detail navigation — any "close section A while opening section B" UI where A and B are instances of the same child component.

#### Root cause

`leavingNodes` is keyed by `TNode` (`packages/core/src/animation/utils.ts:116`):

```ts
export const leavingNodes = new WeakMap<TNode, HTMLElement[]>();
```

A `TNode` belongs to the compiled `TView` and is **shared by every instance** of that template. So the animated element in instance A and the one in instance B map to the *same* `TNode` bucket.

On insert, `applyToElementOrContainer` calls `cancelLeavingNodes(tNode, enteringEl)` (`node_manipulation.ts:154`). Inside (`utils.ts:145-176`), the still-untouched branch fires:

```ts
} else if (
  (prevSibling && leavingEl === prevSibling) ||
  (leavingParent && newParent && leavingParent !== newParent)   // ← A's host !== B's host
) {
  nodes.splice(i, 1);
  leavingEl.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('animationend', {detail: {cancel: true}}));
  leavingEl.parentNode?.removeChild(leavingEl);   // ← A's leaving element ripped out, no animation
}
```

Because A's leaving element and B's entering element are **different DOM nodes** (`leavingEl !== newElement`), the #67361 `reusedNodes` rescue does not apply; execution falls through to `leavingParent !== newParent` and A is removed instantly.

The heuristic was added (PR #67032) to dedupe a single dynamic component re-rendered into a new overlay/portal parent. But "different parent" is also the *normal* situation for two legitimate sibling instances, so it produces false positives.

#### Why it's direction-dependent

Both instances update in the same tick, walked in DOM order, and `cancelLeavingNodes` only removes a leaving node that is *already tracked* when the entering node is inserted:

- **Open a *later* sibling (broken):** the earlier section is detached first → its element is pushed into `leavingNodes[tNode]`; then the later section's element is inserted → `cancelLeavingNodes` finds the tracked node, sees a different parent, and removes it before its `animate.leave` runs.
- **Open an *earlier* sibling (works):** the earlier section's element is *inserted* first, while `leavingNodes[tNode]` is still empty → `cancelLeavingNodes` is a no-op; the later section is detached afterward with no subsequent insert to cancel it, so its `animate.leave` runs to completion.

Measured on the repro (sampling the leaving panel's height per frame, Angular 21.2.17):

```
A open → click B (close A, the earlier section):  A removed at ~47ms,  no animation   ❌
B open → click A (close B, the later section):    B removed at ~637ms, shrink ran     ✅
```

The fix must therefore cover the broken (open-a-later-sibling) direction regardless of position.

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

Minimal standalone reproduction inlined below (a StackBlitz can be provided on request). Two instances of one component, exclusive expansion — one `@if` collapses while a sibling expands.

**`expandable.component.ts`**
```ts
import {Component, EventEmitter, Input, Output} from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-expandable',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    <button (click)="toggle.emit(id)">Toggle {{ id }}</button>
    @if (open) {
      <div class="panel" animate.enter="enter" animate.leave="leave">Panel {{ id }}</div>
    }
  `,
  styles: [`
    .panel { overflow: hidden; background: #def; }
    .enter { animation: grow 600ms ease-in-out; }
    .leave { animation: shrink 600ms ease-in-out forwards; }
    @keyframes grow   { from { height: 0; } to { height: 60px; } }
    @keyframes shrink { from { height: 60px; } to { height: 0; } }
  `],
})
export class ExpandableComponent {
  @Input() id!: string;
  @Input() open = false;
  @Output() toggle = new EventEmitter<string>();
}
```

**`app.component.ts`**
```ts
import {Component} from '@angular/core';
import {ExpandableComponent} from './expandable.component';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [ExpandableComponent],
  // Two instances of the SAME template; only one open at a time.
  template: `
    @for (s of sections; track s) {
      <app-expandable [id]="s" [open]="openId === s" (toggle)="openId = $event" />
    }
  `,
})
export class AppComponent {
  sections = ['A', 'B'];
  openId = 'A';
}
```

### Please provide the steps to reproduce

1. Load the app — section **A** is open.
2. Click **Toggle B**.

### Please provide the exception or error you saw

No error. Visually: B's panel grows in (enter works), but A's panel **disappears instantly** instead of shrinking. Toggling a single section open→closed (without opening another) animates correctly — the bug only appears on a concurrent enter+leave across sibling instances.

### Expected behavior

A's panel should run its `animate.leave` (shrink) animation while B's panel runs `animate.enter` (grow) — both visible simultaneously, as with `@angular/animations` `:enter`/`:leave` and as in Angular ≤ 21.1.

### Anything else relevant?

- Reproduced on **21.2.13**; the offending branch is still present on `main` (`packages/core/src/animation/utils.ts:167-174`).
- Same root mechanism as #67257 (drag-drop). PR #67361 only rescued the *node-move* case (`leavingEl === newElement`); the cross-parent removal for **distinct sibling-instance elements** remains.
- Confirming the mechanism in DevTools: patching `Element.prototype.getAnimations` shows that at Angular's post-insert `requestAnimationFrame` check, the leaving element reports `isConnected === false` and `getAnimations().length === 0` (it has already been `removeChild`-ed), so `determineLongestAnimation` finds nothing and treats it as "no animation → remove now." A synthetic `animationend` `CustomEvent` with `{detail:{cancel:true}}` is observed on the leaving element immediately before its removal — the signature of `cancelLeavingNodes`.
- Suggested direction: the cross-parent (`leavingParent !== newParent`) removal should not fire when the leaving and entering elements belong to **different component instances of the same `TNode`** (i.e. distinct, both-connected nodes that are not a move). Keying/scoping the dedup by instance (`LView`) rather than purely by `TNode`, or restricting the cross-parent removal to the dynamic-component/portal case it was written for, would avoid the false positive.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

forms

### Is this a regression?

No — long-standing in spirit (`NgControlStatus` vs OnPush, #11563, filed 2016). The signal-backed control state added for signal-forms interop fixes most template shapes, but not this one.

### Description

`NgForm` registers `ngModel` / `ngModelGroup` controls in a deferred microtask (`resolvedPromise.then(...)` in `NgForm.addControl` / `addFormGroup` / `removeControl` — [`ng_form.ts`](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/packages/forms/src/directives/ng_form.ts)), without marking any view dirty.

`NgControlStatusGroup`'s host bindings (`AbstractControlStatus`, [`ng_control_status.ts`](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/packages/forms/src/directives/ng_control_status.ts)) create reactive dependencies by reading the control's internal signals:

```ts
get isTouched() {
  this._cd?.control?._touched?.();   // signal read → dependency
  return !!this._cd?.control?.touched;
}
```

When the host bindings are first checked **before** the deferred registration has run, `control` is still `undefined`, the optional chain short-circuits, and **no signal dependency is created** — so nothing ever notifies the view about the group's state.

If any control registers *beneath* the group (an `<input ngModel>` in the same view or in a child view), the registration wave's signal writes end up waking the relevant views and the group host recovers. But when the group has **no rendered controls** — the classic collapsed accordion/section pattern, where the group element renders and its content is `@if`-ed out — there is nothing to wake the view, ever:

- the group **is** correctly registered in the model (`form.get('...')` exists, `valid`/`touched`/`pristine` are all correct), but
- the group host's `ng-untouched` / `ng-pristine` / `ng-valid` classes **never appear**, and **later model changes (e.g. `markAllAsTouched()`) are never reflected either** — permanently stale DOM in zoneless OnPush apps.

Side observation: `isUntouched`, `isDirty`, `isInvalid` and `isPending` don't read the corresponding signals at all (their positive counterparts do). They're rescued today by being evaluated in the same host-binding pass, but the asymmetry looks unintentional.

**What the reproduction shows** (link below; Angular 21.2.16, zoneless): two `ngModelGroup` boxes in a real form, styled purely via their status classes (`.ng-valid` green / `.ng-invalid` red / `.ng-touched` yellow), with the live model state printed under each:

- **BROKEN** (OnPush view, group content not rendered — "collapsed section"): model says `valid=true touched=false` → the box should be green; it has **no `ng-*` classes at all**, ever.
- **CONTROL** (identical OnPush component, input rendered in the same view): correctly red (`ng-invalid`).
- Click **`form.markAllAsTouched()`**: the model reports `touched=true` for both groups; the CONTROL box turns yellow (`ng-touched`); the BROKEN box still shows nothing.

The essential shape:

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'broken-group',
  // a "collapsed section": the group host renders, its inputs do not
  template: `<div ngModelGroup="broken">collapsed section</div>`,
  imports: [FormsModule],
  viewProviders: [{ provide: ControlContainer, useExisting: NgForm }],
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
})
class BrokenGroupComponent {}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `<form><broken-group /></form>`,
  imports: [FormsModule, BrokenGroupComponent],
})
class AppComponent {}

bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, {
  providers: [provideZonelessChangeDetection()],
});
```

Remove `changeDetection: OnPush`, or render an `<input ngModel>` inside the group, and the classes behave as expected.

**NG0100 flavor under exhaustive checkNoChanges:** the same stale binding makes `provideCheckNoChangesConfig({exhaustive: true})` — the recommended dev-time net for zoneless apps — throw `NG0100` on every tick after the deferred registration lands. TestBed reproduction (verified on 21.2.16, ChromeHeadless):

```ts
it("throws NG0100 for ngModelGroup ng-* classes (exhaustive checkNoChanges)", async () => {
  TestBed.configureTestingModule({
    providers: [
      provideZonelessChangeDetection(),
      provideCheckNoChangesConfig({ exhaustive: true }),
    ],
  });
  const appRef = TestBed.inject(ApplicationRef);
  const host = document.createElement("div");
  document.body.appendChild(host);
  const compRef = createComponent(AppComponent, {  // <form><broken-group/></form> as above
    environmentInjector: TestBed.inject(EnvironmentInjector),
    hostElement: host,
  });
  appRef.attachView(compRef.hostView);
  appRef.tick();
  await new Promise<void>((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve)); // let NgForm's deferred registration run
  expect(() => appRef.tick()).toThrowError(/NG0100/);
  host.remove();
});
```

In our application (large template-driven-forms app, ~30 templates with `ngModelGroup` in OnPush components, per-item groups with collapsible content) this throws on every render of a collapsed section. The only workaround is `exhaustive: false`, which also hides real findings.

With v22 defaulting components to OnPush and pushing zoneless, this shape stops being exotic. Possible directions:

1. Have `NgForm`'s deferred registration notify the registering directive's host view (mark it for refresh once the `resolvedPromise.then` lands), or
2. give `AbstractControlStatus` a dependency it can track before the control exists (e.g. a "control resolved" signal on the directive), and make the negative getters (`isUntouched`/`isDirty`/`isInvalid`/`isPending`) read the same signals as their positive counterparts;
3. at minimum, document on `provideCheckNoChangesConfig` that exhaustive mode produces unavoidable NG0100s with template-driven forms in OnPush views of this shape.

